          "prompt_html": "<h1>NOTE COMPLETION 38</h1><p><strong>Questions 31 - 40</strong></p><p>Complete the notes.</p><p>Use <strong>NO MORE THAN ONE WORD</strong> for each answer.</p><table><thead><tr><th>| SWOT Analysis |<br>| --- |<br><strong>What is SWOT?</strong><br>A business planning analysis framework.<br>Thought to come from Stanford Research Institute. Originally wanted an explanation for the <blank data-qid=\"q31\"/> of existing planning methods.<br>SWOT stands for Strengths, Weaknesses, Opportunities and Threats.<br><strong>Internal/External</strong><br>Internal factors - <blank data-qid=\"q32\"/> that could give it advantage or disadvantage. Strengths and weaknesses.<br>Examples: product / service / price / a company's <blank data-qid=\"q33\"/> / company’s financial situation and manufacturing capabilities.<br>External factors - things that are out of your <blank data-qid=\"q34\"/>. Could benefit you or cause problems. Opportunities and threats.<br>Examples: activities of your <blank data-qid=\"q35\"/> and changes in society.<br><strong>Uses for SWOT Analysis</strong><br>Some existing companies perform SWOT analysis every <blank data-qid=\"q36\"/> to assess the marketplace. New companies perform one as part of planning process.<br><blank data-qid=\"q37\"/> departments carry out SWOT analyses on rivals.<br>Non-profit organisations and <blank data-qid=\"q38\"/> projects also perform them to help create objectives and goals.<br><strong>Drawbacks to SWOT analysis</strong><br>Can <blank data-qid=\"q39\"/> a complex situation.<br>It is too subjective – somebody makes a judgement on what is good or bad.<br>All identified areas are identically <blank data-qid=\"q40\"/><br>.</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td></td></tr></tbody></table>",
